async/await is one of the most widely used features in modern JavaScript because it makes asynchronous code look and feel like synchronous code.
However, many developers assume that await blocks JavaScript execution like a traditional synchronous operation. In reality, await works closely with the JavaScript Event Loop, Promises, and the Microtask Queue.
Understanding what happens behind the scenes can help you write more efficient code and avoid unexpected behavior.
What is async/await?
An async function always returns a Promise.
async function greet() {
return "Hello";
}greet().then(console.log);
Output
HelloEven though we’re returning a simple string, JavaScript automatically wraps it in a Promise.
What Does await Actually Do?
The await keyword pauses the execution of the current async function until the Promise settles.
Many developers interpret this as “JavaScript stops here.”
That’s not entirely true.
While the async function pauses, the JavaScript engine remains free to execute other tasks.
Example:
async function demo() {
console.log("Before await");await Promise.resolve();
console.log("After await");
}
demo();
console.log("Outside function");
Output
Before await
Outside function
After awaitEven though the Promise resolves immediately, execution after await is deferred.
The Event Loop’s Role
JavaScript has:

• Call Stack

• Web APIs (or Node.js APIs)

• Task Queue (Macrotask Queue)

• Microtask Queue

• Event Loop
When an await is encountered:

• The current async function pauses.

• The remaining code is wrapped as a Promise continuation.

• That continuation is placed in the Microtask Queue.

• The Event Loop executes it when the Call Stack becomes empty.
Visualizing the Flow
Consider this code:
console.log("Start");async function run() {
console.log("Inside");
await Promise.resolve();
console.log("After await");
}
run();
console.log("End");
