After awaitasync/await and Promises Use the Same Queue
Many developers don’t realize that await is built on top of Promises.
Consider:
Promise.resolve().then(() => {
console.log("Promise");
});async function demo() {
await Promise.resolve();
console.log("Await");
}
demo();
Output
Promise
AwaitBoth operations use the Microtask Queue.
The order depends on which Microtask was queued first.
Microtasks vs setTimeout()
One of the most important concepts is that Microtasks have higher priority than Macrotasks.
Example:
setTimeout(() => {
console.log("Timeout");
}, 0);async function demo() {
await Promise.resolve();
console.log("Await");
}
demo();
console.log("End");
Output
End
Await
TimeoutWhy?
Because:

• console.log("End") runs synchronously.

• await schedules a Microtask.

• setTimeout() schedules a Macrotask.

• Event Loop always clears all Microtasks before processing the next Macrotask.
Multiple await Statements
Each await creates a new pause point.
async function demo() {
console.log("1");await Promise.resolve();
console.log("2");
await Promise.resolve();
console.log("3");
}
demo();
console.log("4");
Output
1
4
2
3The function resumes after each Promise resolution.
Does await Block the Event Loop?
No.
Example:
async function fetchData() {
console.log("Start");await new Promise(resolve => {
setTimeout(resolve, 3000);
});
console.log("Finished");
}
fetchData();
console.log("Application still running");
Immediate Output
Start
Application still runningAfter 3 Seconds
FinishedThe Event Loop continues processing other tasks while the Promise is pending.
A Common Interview Question
What will this print?
console.log("A");setTimeout(() => {
console.log("B");
}, 0);
(async () => {
console.log("C");
await Promise.resolve();
console.log("D");
})();
console.log("E");
Answer
A
C
E
D
BExplanation

• A executes.

• setTimeout() schedules a Macrotask.

• C executes.

• await schedules a Microtask.

• E executes.

• Microtasks run → D.

• Macrotasks run → B.
What Happens Internally?
This:
async function demo() {
await somePromise();
console.log("Done");
}is conceptually similar to:
function demo() {
return Promise.resolve(somePromise())
.then(() => {
console.log("Done");
});
}The Event Loop treats both in a very similar way because await is built on top of Promise chaining.
Summary
async/await does not block JavaScript execution. When JavaScript encounters an await, it pauses only the current async function and places the remaining code into the Microtask Queue.
The Event Loop then:

• Finishes all synchronous code.

• Executes all pending Microtasks (Promises and async/await continuations).

• Processes Macrotasks such as setTimeout() and setInterval().
This is why code after an await often runs before setTimeout(fn, 0). Understanding this relationship between async/await, Promises, Microtasks, and the Event Loop is essential for writing predictable and efficient JavaScript applications.
